50-//
51-// Iter-11 context-aware-rule state (line-scoped):
52-//   A single bool `sawColonThisLine` is threaded through both passes of
53-//   the scanner. It is FALSE at start-of-buffer; set to TRUE the FIRST
54-//   time the scanner encounters a `:` on the current logical line; reset
55-//   to FALSE on every `\n`. Rules B and C only fire when this flag is
56-//   already TRUE at the matching `:` position -- i.e. the rule attempts
57-//   to strip a SECOND `:` on the same line, which is the SM4+-illegal
58-//   stacked-semantic-on-struct-member shape (`: POSITION0 : register(v0)`).
59-//   On the FIRST `:` of a line (e.g. a global `float4 foo : register(c0);`
60-//   in vertex_shader_constants.inc), the flag is still FALSE, the rule
61-//   returns 0, and the binding is preserved verbatim -- which is exactly
62-//   what SM4+ requires for global register bindings.
63-//
64-//   This context check was added in Iter-11 after Iter-10's diagnostic
65-//   dumps revealed that Iter-7..Iter-10's rules were OVER-STRIPPING:
66://   they stripped `: register(cN)` regardless of whether the `:` was
67-//   the first colon (global -- binding is LEGAL and required) or a
68-//   subsequent colon (struct-member stacked semantic -- binding is
69-//   ILLEGAL under SM4+). The over-strip removed all bindings from
70-//   vertex_shader_constants.inc's ~15 global declarations including
71-//   the multi-register `LightData lightData : register(c16)` struct,
72-//   forcing D3DCompile's auto-allocator to invent non-overlapping
73-//   placements -- which it could not, emitting X4016.
74-//
75-// Order matters: Rule C is tried BEFORE Rule B because Rule C is a
76-// superset / more-specific match starting at the same `:` position.
77-// (Both rules start at `:`; Rule C's pattern is longer when it matches,
78-// so we try the longer one first to avoid Rule B greedily eating the
79-// `:` of a Rule-C-eligible site.)
80-//
81-// Two-pass strategy:
82-//   Pass 1 (computeRewrittenLength) -- walks the buffer once and returns
--
731-			if (ch == '\n')
